ese myths and how they might be dispelled at a time when, away from the public gaze, economic theory is opening up new possibilities of economic action. Possibilities that, as we emerge from the chaos of COVID-19, could lead to the radical structural changes we desperately need.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEconomicszGreat Britain. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Economy.2bisacsh  aGreen New Deal.  aHabermas.  aausterity.  acivil service.  afinancial press.  afinancialization.  ainequality.  amodern monetary theory.  apopulism.  apost-COVID-19 economy.  apost-Keynesian.1 aMosse, Jack, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152616139040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526161390423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526161390/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles